in the stomach","Occurs via active transport in the colon","Requires bile acids and occurs in the duodenum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin B12 absorption \u003Cstrong\u003Erequires intrinsic factor and occurs in the ileum\u003C/strong\u003E. Intrinsic factor is produced by gastric parietal cells and forms a complex with vitamin B12. This complex then binds to specific receptors in the ileum where it is absorbed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires pepsin and occurs in the stomach\u003C/strong\u003E - While pepsin helps break down proteins, it is not directly involved in B12 absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires bile acids and occurs in the duodenum\u003C/strong\u003E - While bile acids help with fat absorption, they are not required for B12 absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires calcium and occurs in the stomach\u003C/strong\u003E - The stomach releases B12 from food proteins but does not absorb it\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport in the colon\u003C/strong\u003E - B12 absorption is complete before reaching the colon\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDeficiency of intrinsic factor, as occurs in pernicious anaemia or after gastric surgery, leads to vitamin B12 deficiency and subsequent megaloblastic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin B12 absorption requires intrinsic factor produced by gastric parietal cells to facilitate transport across the ileal membrane.","Vitamin B12 is essential for DNA synthesis and myelin formation.","Dietary sources of vitamin B12 include meat, fish, eggs and dairy products."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56960"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17587"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56960"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T17:12:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T17:12:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10277"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71451"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCou